Definition: Given a list of n elements, list all the combinations of choosing n-1 elements from this list. The output should have n lists with each list having n-1 elements.

Positive Examples.explanation: The output is a list of length 5, containing lists of length 4. Also, no element from the input list is repeated in the inner lists of the output. So this is a good example.

The character 'j' appeared in the input list twice, therefore it appears twice in an inner list in the output. This is not repeating an element because they are different elements. So this is a good example.

Negative Examples.explanation: The output only chooses one element from the input list. So this is a bad example.
The output only contains one possible combination of choosing 'n - 1' elements. So this is a bad example.
The output does not include combinations where both '5' elements are chosen. They are different elements, therefore you are able to choose both. So this is a bad example.
